{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"33158fcf-1f53-43ab-abf9-621b3e1ce4b9","content":"In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Created\");\n    window.Activated     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Activated\");\n    window.Deactivated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Deactivated\");\n    window.Stopped       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Stopped\");\n    window.Resumed       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Resumed\");\n    window.Destroying    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Destroying\");\n    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Backgrounding\");\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Typical transition order:**\n\n| Scenario | Events |\n|---|---|\n| App launch | `Created → Activated` |\n| Switched away | `Deactivated → Stopped` |\n| Switched back | `Resumed → Activated` |\n| App closed | `Deactivated → Stopped → Destroying` |\n| iOS background | `Backgrounding` (before `Stopped`) |\n\n> `Backgrounding` is iOS-specific — use it to save state. On Android/Windows the `Stopped` event serves the same purpose.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ccd59c83-3dc0-465d-a833-b4f74364064f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI Window lifecycle events and how to subscribe to them for debugging/logging purposes. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI development - I can answer this directly without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":431,"requestId":"9817:23A6C6:1562F12:17F5A2B:6A051EA6"},"id":"b5bb7e2d-ddb1-44d3-a14b-f227746f06a8","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:00:30.767Z","parentId":"3552a96c-0cba-4fd3-8a38-30a90aa194f5"}
